href="android-app://org.wikipedia/http/en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sue_Bailey_Thurman"/>\n<link rel="alternate" type="application/x-wiki" title="Edit this page" href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit"/>\n<link rel="edit" title="Edit this page" href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit"/>\n<link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/static/apple-touch/wikipedia.png"/>\n<link rel="shortcut icon" href="/static/favicon/wikipedia.ico"/>\n<link rel="search" type="application/opensearchdescription+xml" href="/w/opensearch_desc.php" title="Wikipedia (en)"/>\n<link rel="EditURI" type="application/rsd+xml" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd"/>\n<link rel="license" href="//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/"/>\n<link rel="canonical" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sue_Bailey_Thurman"/>\n<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//login.wikimedia.org"/>\n<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//meta.wikimedia.org" />\n<!--[if lt IE 9]><script src="/resources/lib/html5shiv/html5shiv.min.js"></script><![endif]-->\n</head>\n<body class="mediawiki ltr sitedir-ltr mw-hide-empty-elt ns-0 ns-subject page-Sue_Bailey_Thurman rootpage-Sue_Bailey_Thurman skin-vector action-view">\t\t<div id="mw-page-base" class="noprint"></div>\n\t\t<div id="mw-head-base" class="noprint"></div>\n\t\t<div id="content" class="mw-body" role="main">\n\t\t\t<a id="top"></a>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="siteNotice" class="mw-body-content"><!-- CentralNotice --></div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="mw-indicators mw-body-content">\n<div id="mw-indicator-good-star" class="mw-indicator"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Good_articles" title="This is a good article. Click here for more information."><img alt="This is a good article. Click here for more information." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/19px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png" width="19" height="20" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/29px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/39px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="180" data-file-height="185" /></a></div>\n</div>\n\t\t\t<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Sue Bailey Thurman</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="contentSub"></div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">\n\t\t\t\t\tJump to:\t\t\t\t\t<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, \t\t\t\t\t<a href="#p-search">search</a>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><table class="infobox biography vcard" style="width:22em">\n<tr>\n<th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold"><span class="fn">Sue Bailey Thurman</span></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:Sue_Bailey_Thurman.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Sue Bailey Thurman.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/1/1f/Sue_Bailey_Thurman.jpg" width="202" height="194" data-file-width="202" data-file-height="194" /></a>\n<div>Sue Bailey Thurman, 1953</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">Born</th>\n<td><span class="nickname">Sue Elvie Bailey</span><br />\n<span style="display:none">(<span class="bday">1903-08-26</span>)</span>August 26, 1903<br />\n<span class="birthplace"><a href="/wiki/Pine_Bluff,_Arkansas" title="Pine Bluff, Arkansas">Pine Bluff, Arkansas</a></span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">Died</th>\n<td>December 25, 1996<span style="display:none">(<span class="dday deathdate">1996-12-25</span>)</span> (aged&#160;93)<br />\n<span class="deathplace"><a href="/wiki/San_Francisco" title="San Francisco">San Francisco</a>, California</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">Nationality</th>\n<td class="category">American</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">Occupation</th>\n<td class="role">writer, lecturer, historian, civil rights activist</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th scope="row">Years&#160;active</th>\n<td>1926\xe2\x80\x9395</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<p><b>Sue Bailey Thurman</b> (n\xc3\xa9e, <b>Sue Elvie Bailey</b>; August 26, 1903 \xe2\x80\x93 December 25, 1996) was an American author, lecturer, historian and civil rights activist. She was the first non-white student to earn a bachelor\'s degree in music from <a href="/wiki/Oberlin_College" title="Oberlin College">Oberlin College</a>, Ohio. She briefly taught at the <a href="/wiki/Hampton_Institute" class="mw-redirect" title="Hampton Institute">Hampton Institute</a> in Virginia, before becoming involved in <a href="/wiki/Internationalism_(politics)" title="Internationalism (politics)">international work</a> with the <a href="/wiki/YWCA" title="YWCA">YWCA</a> in 1930. During a six-month trip through Asia in the mid 1930s, Thurman became the first <a href="/wiki/African_American" class="mw-redirect" title="African American">African-American</a> woman to have an audience with <a href="/wiki/Mahatma_Gandhi" title="Mahatma Gandhi">Mahatma Gandhi</a>. The meeting with Gandhi inspired Thurman and her husband, theologian <a href="/wiki/Howard_Thurman" title="Howard Thurman">Howard Thurman</a>, to promote non-violent resistance as a means of creating social change, bringing it to the attention of a young preacher, <a href="/wiki/Martin_Luther_King_Jr." title="Martin Luther King Jr.">Martin Luther King Jr.</a> While they did not actively protest during the <a href="/wiki/Civil_Rights_Movement" class="mw-redirect" title="Civil Rights Movement">Civil Rights Movement</a>, they served as spiritual counselors to many on the front lines, and helped establish the first interracial, <a href="/wiki/Non-denominational" title="Non-denominational">non-denominational</a> church in the United States.</p>\n<p>Thurman played an active role in establishing international student organizations to help prevent foreign students feeling isolated while studying abroad. She organized one of the first international scholarship programs for African-American women. She studied racism and the effects of prejudice on various people throughout the world, making two round-the-world trips in her lifetime. She wrote books and newspaper articles to preserve black heritage, and initiated the publishing efforts of the <a href="/wiki/National_Council_of_Negro_Women" title="National Council of Negro Women">National Council of Negro Women</a> (NCNW) by founding the <i>Aframerican Women\xe2\x80\x99s Journal</i>. In addition to writing the second ever history of black Californians, in 1958 Thurman published a cookbook laced with historical information about black professional women at a time when African Americans had few civil rights. Recognizing that there was little academic interest in black women\'s history at the time, Thurman used the marketing ploy of food to report on the lives of black women who were not domestics. She participated in international peace and feminist conferences, and in 1945 attended the San Francisco Conference for the founding of the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> as part of an unofficial delegation. Thurman also established museums such as the <a href="/wiki/Museum_of_Afro-American_History" class="mw-redirect" title="Museum of Afro-American History">Museum of Afro-American History</a> in <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a> in 1963.</p>\n<p>Thurman and her husband retired in San Francisco in 1965. She worked with the <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_Public_Library" title="San Francisco Public Library">San Francisco Public Library</a> in 1969 to develop resources for black history of the American West. In 1979 she was honored with a Centennial Award at <a href="/wiki/Spelman_College" title="Spelman College">Spelman College</a>, sharing the recognition with <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">UNESCO</a> director Herschelle Sullivan Challenor. After her husband\'s death in 1981, Thurman took over the management of the Howard Thurman Educational Trust, which funded research for literary, religious and scientific purposes and assisted in scholarships for black students. On her death in 1996, she left the couple\'s vast archives to numerous universities.</p>\n<p></p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc">\n<div class="toctitle">\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#Early_years"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">Early years</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-2"><a href="#Early_career"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">Early career</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-3"><a href="#Asia"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">Asia</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-4"><a href="#Mid-career"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">Mid-career</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-5"><a href="#Scholarly_work_and_San_Francisco"><span class="tocnumber">4.1</span> <span class="toctext">Scholarly work and San Francisco</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-6"><a href="#Boston"><span class="tocnumber">4.2</span> <span class="toctext">Boston</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-7"><a href="#San_Francisco_return"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span class="toctext">San Francisco return</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-8"><a href="#Legacy"><span class="tocnumber">6</span> <span class="toctext">Legacy</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-9"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">7</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-10"><a href="#Further_reading"><span class="tocnumber">8</span> <span class="toctext">Further reading</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_years">Early years</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Early years">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:OberlinArchSmall.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/OberlinArchSmall.jpg/220px-OberlinArchSmall.jpg" width="220" height="107" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/OberlinArchSmall.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="324" data-file-height="158" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:OberlinArchSmall.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nOberlin College</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Sue Elvie Bailey was born on August 26, 1903, in <a href="/wiki/Pine_Bluff,_Arkansas" title="Pine Bluff, Arkansas">Pine Bluff, Arkansas</a>, to Reverend Isaac and Susie (n\xc3\xa9e Ford) Bailey.<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> She attended primary school at <a href="/wiki/Nannie_Helen_Burroughs_School" title="Nannie Helen Burroughs School">Nannie Burroughs\' School for Girls</a> in Washington, D.C.<sup id="cite_ref-Hill_.281991.29_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hill_.281991.29-2">[2]</a></sup> In 1920, she graduated from the college preparatory school, Spelman Seminary (now <a href="/wiki/Spelman_College" title="Spelman College">Spelman College</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> in <a href="/wiki/Atlanta" title="Atlanta">Atlanta</a>, <a href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Jet_Magazine_Obit_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jet_Magazine_Obit-3">[3]</a></sup> She continued her education at <a href="/wiki/Oberlin_College" title="Oberlin College">Oberlin College</a> in <a href="/wiki/Oberlin,_Ohio" title="Oberlin, Ohio">Oberlin</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ohio" title="Ohio">Ohio</a>, graduating in 1926 with bachelor\'s degrees in music and liberal arts,<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> making her the first black student to earn a music degree from Oberlin.<sup id="cite_ref-firsts_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firsts-4">[4]</a></sup> While there, Bailey developed a friendship with <a href="/wiki/Louise_Thompson_Patterson" title="Louise Thompson Patterson">Louise Thompson</a>, who would become a central figure in the <a href="/wiki/Harlem_Renaissance" title="Harlem Renaissance">Harlem Renaissance</a> movement, and encouraged <a href="/wiki/Langston_Hughes" title="Langston Hughes">Langston Hughes</a>, inventor of <a href="/wiki/Jazz_poetry" title="Jazz poetry">jazz poetry</a>, to read poetry there.<sup id="cite_ref-Rampersad_.282001.29_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rampersad_.282001.29-5">[5]</a></sup> She traveled with a quintet giving concerts in <a href="/wiki/Cleveland" title="Cleveland">Cleveland</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_(state)" title="New York (state)">New York</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia" title="Philadelphia">Philadelphia</a>, as well as London and Paris.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_career">Early career</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Early career">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>After graduating, Thurman took a post as a music teacher at the <a href="/wiki/Hampton_Institute" class="mw-redirect" title="Hampton Institute">Hampton Institute</a> in Virginia, but did not enjoy the work.<sup id="cite_ref-firsts_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firsts-4">[4]</a></sup> One of the issues at Hampton was that her friend, Louise Thompson, also a teacher there, had written anonymously to <a href="/wiki/W._E._B._Du_Bois" title="W. E. B. Du Bois">W. E. B. Du Bois</a>, co-founder of the <a href="/wiki/National_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Colored_People" title="National Association for the Advancement of Colored People">National Association for the Advancement of Colored People</a> (NAACP), complaining about conditions at the college under the predominantly white administration. Although Bailey was suspected of writing the letter after Du Bois published it in the NAACP\'s journal <i><a href="/wiki/The_Crisis" title="The Crisis">The Crisis</a></i>, she did not betray Thompson but instead invited Langston Hughes to Hampton for a poetry reading and moral support.<sup id="cite_ref-Rampersad_.282001.29_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rampersad_.282001.29-5">[5]</a></sup> Nevertheless, she left Hampton in 1930<sup id="cite_ref-firsts_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firsts-4">[4]</a></sup> to become a traveling National Secretary for the Student Division of the <a href="/wiki/YWCA" title="YWCA">YWCA</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> She lectured throughout Europe and established the first World Fellowship Committee of the YWCA.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> On June 12, 1932, in the dining hall at <a href="/wiki/Lincoln_Academy_(Kings_Mountain,_North_Carolina)" title="Lincoln Academy (Kings Mountain, North Carolina)">Lincoln Academy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kings_Mountain,_North_Carolina" title="Kings Mountain, North Carolina">Kings Mountain, North Carolina</a>, Bailey married <a href="/wiki/Howard_Thurman" title="Howard Thurman">Howard W. Thurman</a> (1900\xe2\x80\x931981), a minister, who would become a social critic, writer and dean of several prominent US universities.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> At the time of their marriage, he was serving as Dean of Rankin Chapel and Professor of Systematic Theology at <a href="/wiki/Howard_University" title="Howard University">Howard University</a> in Washington, D.C.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Asia">Asia</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Asia">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tleft">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Tagore_Gandhi.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Tagore_Gandhi.jpg/220px-Tagore_Gandhi.jpg" width="220" height="196" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Tagore_Gandhi.jpg/330px-Tagore_Gandhi.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Tagore_Gandhi.jpg/440px-Tagore_Gandhi.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="912" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Tagore_Gandhi.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nRabindranath Tagore and Mahatma Gandhi</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>In 1935, the couple embarked upon a six-month trip through southern Asia, visiting Burma, Ceylon and India, culminating in a \xe2\x80\x9cPilgrimage of Friendship\xe2\x80\x9d to the International Student Conference in India. Her husband led the American delegation, lecturing at more than forty universities,<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> while Thurman herself was asked to meet with journalists and students, to discuss race relations and evaluate the parallels between the situation with Indians and the British and the African Americans and white Americans.<sup id="cite_ref-On_India_part_1_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-On_India_part_1-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-On_India_part_2_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-On_India_part_2-11">[11]</a></sup> Initially, Howard had turned down the opportunity and his wife was not included in the offer, but when the trip was finally agreed, both were participants.<sup id="cite_ref-Dixie_.26_Eisenstadt_.282011.29_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dixie_.26_Eisenstadt_.282011.29-12">[12]</a></sup> Thurman was not chosen simply as the wife of Howard Thurman but, in the words of the committee, because she was one of "four persons best able to do this particular job".<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> This decision was remarkable for the period given that black women were often invisible members of society<sup id="cite_ref-O.27Brien_.282009.29_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-O.27Brien_.282009.29-14">[14]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Interview_with_Gloria_Goodman_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Interview_with_Gloria_Goodman-15">[15]</a></sup> and generally prohibited from authoritative roles in social welfare programs.<sup id="cite_ref-Mjagkij_.282001.29_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mjagkij_.282001.29-16">[16]</a></sup> Thurman lectured during the trip on negro women and the organizations to which they belonged, as well as <a href="/wiki/Internationalism_(politics)" title="Internationalism (politics)">internationalism</a> and culture.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> During their meeting with <a href="/wiki/Rabindranath_Tagore" title="Rabindranath Tagore">Rabindranath Tagore</a> in <a href="/wiki/Santiniketan" title="Santiniketan">Santiniketan</a> she presented a paper "The History of Negro Music", though initially she had been reluctant to discuss slave music. She finally agreed only after Tagore and Gandhi explained that to Asian Christians, <a href="/wiki/Negro_spirituals" class="mw-redirect" title="Negro spirituals">negro spirituals</a> were deemed to express the profound faith of people even in bondage and seemed more authentic than western <a href="/wiki/Hymns" class="mw-redirect" title="Hymns">hymns</a>. Thurman both sang and taught songs to local choirs.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> She also commented on art, having acquired knowledge on the subject during an earlier trip to Mexico.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></p>\n<p>The couple met with <a href="/wiki/Mahatma_Gandhi" title="Mahatma Gandhi">Mahatma Gandhi</a>, becoming the first African Americans to have an audience with him.<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Jet_Magazine_Obit_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jet_Magazine_Obit-3">[3]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-firsts_4-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firsts-4">[4]</a></sup> When Thurman asked him to take his message to the United States, he demurred as his work in India and his personal quest there were not finished.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> One important aspect of the meeting was a discussion of how non-violent resistance could be used as a means of creating social change.<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> The meeting had a profound effect on the couple, changing the direction of their lives.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> Though they would remain Christians, the meeting with Gandhi led them to consider establishing a church free of prejudice, transcending racial, social, economic and spiritual boundaries. After they returned to the United States, Howard received a letter from <a href="/wiki/A._J._Muste" title="A. J. Muste">A. J. Muste</a> on behalf of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Alfred_Fisk&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Alfred Fisk (page does not exist)">Alfred Fisk</a> who was looking for someone to establish a church in San Francisco which crossed the racial and spiritual divides. Muste was hopeful that Rev. Thurman might know of a divinity student interested in the position. Instead, Howard decided to take up the challenge himself, securing a leave of absence in order to found the church. Thurman went with him bringing their two daughters, as she strongly believed in the cause.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29-22">[22]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Mid-career">Mid-career</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Mid-career">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Scholarly_work_and_San_Francisco">Scholarly work and San Francisco</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Scholarly work and San Francisco">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Thurman established the <a href="/wiki/Juliette_Derricotte" title="Juliette Derricotte">Juliette Derricotte</a> Scholarship in the late 1930s, which allowed African-American undergraduate women of high academic achievement to study and travel abroad.<sup id="cite_ref-Juliette_Derricotte_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Juliette_Derricotte-23">[23]</a></sup> The first two recipients of the scholarship were Marian Banfield of Howard University and <a href="/wiki/Anna_V._Brown" title="Anna V. Brown">Anna V. Brown</a> of Oberlin College.<sup id="cite_ref-scholarship_awards_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-scholarship_awards-24">[24]</a></sup> Banfield was a goddaughter of Howard Thurman.<sup id="cite_ref-Banfield_JPS_link_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Banfield_JPS_link-25">[25]</a></sup> The following year the recipients of her scholarship were Elizabeth McCree from Boston, who attended <a href="/wiki/Fisk_University" title="Fisk University">Fisk University</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-1940_awards_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1940_awards-26">[26]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Margaret_Bush_Wilson" title="Margaret Bush Wilson">Margaret Bush Wilson</a> of Talladega College.<sup id="cite_ref-Juliette_Derricotte_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Juliette_Derricotte-23">[23]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg/220px-Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg/330px-Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg/440px-Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="800" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nMary McLeod Bethune Council House</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>In 1940, Thurman founded the <i>Aframerican Women\xe2\x80\x99s Journal</i>, the first publishing vehicle of the <a href="/wiki/National_Council_of_Negro_Women" title="National Council of Negro Women">National Council of Negro Women</a> (NCNW), which she edited from 1940 until 1944.<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> In 1941, an archive committee was formed to design a plan for collecting works about the achievements of African-American women. Though their plans focused primarily on written records and professional accomplishment and would thus reflect middle-class life, the committee initiated work on collecting historical records of black women. In 1944, Thurman became the committee\'s chair and her mother donated $1,000<sup id="cite_ref-Jardins_.282003.29_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jardins_.282003.29-27">[27]</a></sup> toward creating the National Council of Negro Women\'s National Library, Archives, and Museum.<sup id="cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1">[1]</a></sup> On June 30, 1946, they held an archive drive, printing notices in newsletters and asking ministers, organizations, librarians and others to help them acquire photographs, books and mementos.<sup id="cite_ref-Jardins_.282003.29_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jardins_.282003.29-27">[27]</a></sup> They opened the first facility of the library at what is now the <a href="/wiki/Mary_McLeod_Bethune_Council_House_National_Historic_Site" title="Mary McLeod Bethune Council House National Historic Site">Mary McLeod Bethune Council House National Historic Site</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Dubrow_.26_Goodman_.282003.29_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dubrow_.26_Goodman_.282003.29-28">[28]</a></sup></p>\n<p>In 1943,<sup id="cite_ref-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29-22">[22]</a></sup> Thurman and her husband moved to San Francisco.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> She wrote several articles about their Asian trip,<sup id="cite_ref-On_India_part_1_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-On_India_part_1-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-On_India_part_2_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-On_India_part_2-11">[11]</a></sup> analyzing information, discussing their meeting with Gandhi<sup id="cite_ref-Gandhi_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gandhi-29">[29]</a></sup> and pressing for scholarship exchanges for negro students at Indian universities.<sup id="cite_ref-scholarships_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-scholarships-30">[30]</a></sup> It was from the Thurmans and their talks and writings that <a href="/wiki/Martin_Luther_King_Jr." title="Martin Luther King Jr.">Martin Luther King Jr.</a> learned of non-violent resistance as a means of social protest.<sup id="cite_ref-Hill_.281991.29_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hill_.281991.29-2">[2]</a></sup> By 1944, the church which they had envisioned after their meeting with Gandhi became a reality when they, along with Fisk, opened the <a href="/wiki/Church_for_the_Fellowship_of_All_Peoples" title="Church for the Fellowship of All Peoples">Church for the Fellowship of All Peoples</a>. It was the first interracial, non-denominational church in the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-SF_obituary_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SF_obituary-31">[31]</a></sup> While her husband assumed the pastoral duties, Thurman organized forums and lectures for the members to learn about other peoples such as Native Americans, Africans, Asians and their cultures, covering everything from the Jews to the <a href="/wiki/Navajo_people" class="mw-redirect" title="Navajo people">Navajos</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29_22-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Atlantic_Monthly_.281953.29-22">[22]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tleft">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG/220px-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG" width="220" height="287" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG/330px-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/18/Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG 2x" data-file-width="390" data-file-height="509" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_in_California.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\n"Pioneers of Negro Origin in California" by Sue Bailey Thurman</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>In 1945, Thurman attended the San Francisco Conference for the founding of the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> as part of an unofficial delegation. The official African-American delegation included W. E. B. Du Bois, founder of the NAACP; <a href="/wiki/Walter_Francis_White" title="Walter Francis White">Walter Francis White</a>, Executive Secretary of the NAACP; and <a href="/wiki/Mary_McLeod_Bethune" title="Mary McLeod Bethune">Mary McLeod Bethune</a> founder of the National Council of Negro Women, but Bethune insisted on sending three additional observers from the NCNW, which included Thurman. After the event, Thurman published a report in the <i>Chicago Defender</i> on April 16, 1945, in which she questioned the limited role that <a href="/wiki/People_of_color" class="mw-redirect" title="People of color">people of color</a> played in the proceedings and pointed out that the large populations of developing countries would become a force to be reckoned with.<sup id="cite_ref-United_Nations_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-United_Nations-32">[32]</a></sup> Thurman, as a representative for the NCNW, attended the <a href="/wiki/Primer_Congreso_Interamericano_de_Mujeres" title="Primer Congreso Interamericano de Mujeres">Primer Congreso Interamericano de Mujeres</a> held in Guatemala City, Guatemala, in 1947.<sup id="cite_ref-Primer_Congreso_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Primer_Congreso-33">[33]</a></sup> The congress addressed many of the issues she supported such as women\'s rights, internationalism, and peace initiatives.<sup id="cite_ref-Flores_Asturias_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Flores_Asturias-34">[34]</a></sup> In 1949,<sup id="cite_ref-Thurman_.281979.29_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thurman_.281979.29-35">[35]</a></sup> she led a delegation of members from the Church for the Fellowship of All Peoples to Paris for the Fourth Plenary Session of <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">UNESCO</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup></p>\n<p>After researching black history in California, Thurman wrote eight articles for the <i>San Francisco Sun Reporter</i> as part of a series entitled "Pioneers of Negro Origin in California".<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> Using the same title, she published the articles in book form in 1952.<sup id="cite_ref-pioneers_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pioneers-36">[36]</a></sup> It was the second history of black Californians published\xe2\x80\x94the first being <i>The Negro Trail Blazers of California</i> by <a href="/wiki/Delilah_L._Beasley" title="Delilah L. Beasley">Delilah L. Beasley</a> in 1919\xe2\x80\x94and filled a gap caused by a lack of academic interest.<sup id="cite_ref-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin-37">[37]</a></sup> History in America, at the time, was written about men and almost exclusively about white men.<sup id="cite_ref-Bower_.282009.29_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bower_.282009.29-38">[38]</a></sup> Neither of the women who wrote about the history of blacks in California was a native Californian.<sup id="cite_ref-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin_37-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pioneers_of_Negro_Origin-37">[37]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Boston">Boston</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Boston">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tleft">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG/220px-The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG" width="220" height="152" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG/330px-The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG/440px-The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG 2x" data-file-width="795" data-file-height="549" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Historical_Cookbook_of_the_American_Negro.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nCookbook by Sue Bailey Thurman</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>In 1953, Howard Thurman became the Dean of the <a href="/wiki/Boston_University" title="Boston University">Boston University</a> School of Theology and, after ten years in California, the couple moved to Boston.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> The move was prompted by the desire to share their ideas of outreach and inclusion in a university setting, though they were aware that the arrival of the first black pastor in a white university would lead to difficulties.<sup id="cite_ref-Thurman_.282014.29_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thurman_.282014.29-39">[39]</a></sup> From the beginning, Thurman tried to create an inclusive environment, organizing monthly dinners for the Marsh Chapel Choir members and their friends.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> Shortly after they arrived, a Japanese student committed suicide leaving a note that she had no friends. Not only was she not known well at the university, finding her family to notify them was difficult.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> In response, Thurman organized the International Student Hostess Committee to keep international students from feeling isolated.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> By 1965, the committee was serving 500 international students at Boston University.<sup id="cite_ref-International_Hostess_Committee_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-International_Hostess_Committee-42">[42]</a></sup> The Thurmans were at times criticized by those who felt they should be visibly active in the <a href="/wiki/Civil_Rights_Movement" class="mw-redirect" title="Civil Rights Movement">Civil Rights Movement</a>, but they believed their commitment was to addressing the spiritual needs of those who were visible, rather than participating in marches, protests and demonstrations.<sup id="cite_ref-inner_not_outer_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-inner_not_outer-43">[43]</a></sup> Among the papers of MLK were many letters from people such as <a href="/wiki/Homer_A._Jack" title="Homer A. Jack">Homer A. Jack</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Carson_.281997.29_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Carson_.281997.29-44">[44]</a></sup> who co-founded the <a href="/wiki/Congress_of_Racial_Equality" title="Congress of Racial Equality">Congress of Racial Equality</a>; <a href="/wiki/Lillian_Smith_(author)" title="Lillian Smith (author)">Lillian Smith</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup> author of the novel <a href="/wiki/Strange_Fruit_(novel)" title="Strange Fruit (novel)">Strange Fruit</a>; <a href="/wiki/Glenn_E._Smiley" title="Glenn E. Smiley">Glenn E. Smiley</a>, national field secretary of <a href="/wiki/Fellowship_of_Reconciliation" title="Fellowship of Reconciliation">Fellowship of Reconciliation</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> as well as King\'s own acknowledgement, which credited their spiritual guidance.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-mentorship_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mentorship-48">[48]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Thurman continued her writing work in Boston. In 1958, she published the <i>The Historical Cookbook of the American Negro</i>, which not only gave recipes but included black history. It retold stories of professional women and history to counter the belief that all black women were maids and domestics at a time when African Americans were excluded from basic civil rights.<sup id="cite_ref-cookbook_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cookbook-49">[49]</a></sup> She recognized that in order to tell their history, a new approach was needed as there was no market for histories of the African Americans. In the preface to her book, she explained she was creating "palatable history", testifying to her shrewd marketing ability.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:African_Meeting_House.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/African_Meeting_House.jpg/220px-African_Meeting_House.jpg" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/African_Meeting_House.jpg/330px-African_Meeting_House.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/African_Meeting_House.jpg/440px-African_Meeting_House.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1728" data-file-height="2304" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:African_Meeting_House.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nThe African Meeting House</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>During the 1960s, the Thurmans traveled widely, making various trips to study racial barriers that prohibited creation of community.<sup id="cite_ref-Thurman_.282014.29_39-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thurman_.282014.29-39">[39]</a></sup> A two-year <a href="/wiki/Sabbatical" title="Sabbatical">sabbatical</a> granted from Boston University made their travels possible.<sup id="cite_ref-retirement_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-retirement-51">[51]</a></sup> In 1962, they journeyed to Saskatchewan, Canada, to meet with tribal leaders about discrimination<sup id="cite_ref-Canada_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Canada-52">[52]</a></sup> and in 1963, they embarked on a trip that included Nigeria, Israel, Hawaii, and California.<sup id="cite_ref-Nigeria.2C_Israel_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Nigeria.2C_Israel-53">[53]</a></sup> In Nigeria, Howard Thurman lectured at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Ibadan" title="University of Ibadan">University of Ibadan</a>. The couple\'s second round-the-world tour took them to Japan, the Philippines and Egypt.<sup id="cite_ref-Thurman_.282014.29_39-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Thurman_.282014.29-39">[39]</a></sup></p>\n<div class="thumb tleft">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG/220px-Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG" width="220" height="188" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG/330px-Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG/440px-Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG 2x" data-file-width="886" data-file-height="756" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Boston_African-American_Heritage_Trail.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nBoston African-American Heritage Trail</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>In 1963,<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> Thurman founded the <a href="/wiki/African_Meeting_House#Museum" title="African Meeting House">Museum of Afro-American History</a> in Boston.<sup id="cite_ref-SF_obituary_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SF_obituary-31">[31]</a></sup> Interested in history, she had discovered a settlement where free blacks had lived prior to the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">Civil War</a> and their 1808 <a href="/wiki/African_Meeting_House" title="African Meeting House">African Meeting House</a>, which housed both Boston\'s first black church and the first segregated public school in the United States. The museum was created to save the site and provide a means to purchase other significant properties for preservation of African-American heritage in the area.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> Thurman also created a map of important African American historical sites in Boston with the help of her daughter, Anne Chiarenza, which she called "Negro Freedom Trails of Boston".<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup> The map highlighted twenty-two points of interest to black history within the city of Boston<sup id="cite_ref-Freedom_trails_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Freedom_trails-55">[55]</a></sup> and was in part created to give black school children a sense that they were part of the history of the city.<sup id="cite_ref-black_history_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-black_history-56">[56]</a></sup> What is today known as the <a href="/wiki/Black_Heritage_Trail" title="Black Heritage Trail">Black Heritage Trail</a> was adapted from Thurman\'s original idea.<sup id="cite_ref-Petronella_.282004.29_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Petronella_.282004.29-57">[57]</a></sup></p>\n<p>While in Boston, in 1962, Thurman arranged for the sculptor <a href="/wiki/Meta_Warrick_Fuller" class="mw-redirect" title="Meta Warrick Fuller">Meta Warrick Fuller</a> to create a commissioned "freedom plaque" for <a href="/wiki/Livingstone_College" title="Livingstone College">Livingstone College</a>, of <a href="/wiki/Salisbury,_North_Carolina" title="Salisbury, North Carolina">Salisbury, North Carolina</a>. Bailey was an invited speaker at Livingstone in 1963 and at that time, in honor of United Nations Day, she donated a collection of dolls representing the member nations to the college.<sup id="cite_ref-Livingstone_dolls_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Livingstone_dolls-58">[58]</a></sup> As far back as the 1930s, Thurman had collected ethnic dolls and given them to universities to promote understanding of cultural differences.<sup id="cite_ref-Jet_Magazine_Obit_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jet_Magazine_Obit-3">[3]</a></sup> In 1967, Livingstone awarded her with an honorary doctorate.<sup id="cite_ref-doctorate.2C_Livingstone_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-doctorate.2C_Livingstone-59">[59]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="San_Francisco_return">San Francisco return</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: San Francisco return">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Howard Thurman took retirement from Boston University in 1965 and the couple moved back to San Francisco.<sup id="cite_ref-retirement_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-retirement-51">[51]</a></sup> Thurman continued to pursue historic preservation. She worked with the <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_Public_Library" title="San Francisco Public Library">San Francisco Public Library</a> in 1969 to develop resources for black history of the American West.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup> In the 1970s, the couple took a trip to the Pacific basin.<sup id="cite_ref-1970_trip_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1970_trip-61">[61]</a></sup> In 1979 she was honored with a Centennial Award at Spelman College, sharing the recognition with <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">UNESCO</a> director Herschelle Sullivan Challenor.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup></p>\n<p>After her husband\'s death, in 1981, Thurman took over the management of the Howard Thurman Educational Trust,<sup id="cite_ref-firsts_4-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firsts-4">[4]</a></sup> which funded research for literary, religious and scientific purposes, endowed scholarships for black students and assisted charitable projects.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> Thurman was the mother of Anne Spencer Thurman<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup> and stepmother to Olive Thurman, her husband\'s daughter with his first wife.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup> Olive was the first wife of actor <a href="/wiki/Victor_Wong_(actor_born_1927)" title="Victor Wong (actor born 1927)">Victor Wong</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup></p>\n<p>Thurman died on Christmas Day, 1996, at the <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_Zen_Center" title="San Francisco Zen Center">San Francisco Zen Buddhist Hospice Center</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-SF_obituary_31-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SF_obituary-31">[31]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Legacy">Legacy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Legacy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>After her death in 1996, she and Howard\'s vast archives were donated per their wishes to numerous universities. The largest collection of their documents is housed at Boston University.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotlieb_7-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotlieb-7">[7]</a></sup> There are additional collections of their writings and works at Oberlin,<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Emory_University" title="Emory University">Emory University</a><sup id="cite_ref-Emory_University_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Emory_University-66">[66]</a></sup> and several other institutions like the National Council of Negro Women\'s archives in Washington, D.C and libraries in Arkansas named for her mother, Mrs. Susie Ford Bailey.<sup id="cite_ref-Oberlin_College_6-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Oberlin_College-6">[6]</a></sup> The collection at Emory University includes the correspondence between the Thurmans and Mrs. Bailey, their personal libraries, and nearly one thousand photographs.<sup id="cite_ref-Higginbotham_.282001_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Higginbotham_.282001-67">[67]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sue_Bailey_Thurman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-biography_Boston_University-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-biography_Boston_University_1-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.bu.edu/thurman/about/dr-thurman/sue-bailey-thurman/">"Sue Bailey Thurman"</a>. <i>Boston University</i>. Boston, Massachusetts: Boston University<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">August 4,</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASue+Bailey+Thurman&amp;rft.atitle=Sue+Bailey+Thurman&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Boston+University&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bu.edu%2Fthurman%2Fabout%2Fdr-thurman%2Fsue-bailey-thurman%2F&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Hill_.281991.29-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Hill_.281991.29_2-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Hill_.281991.29_2-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Hill, Ruth Edmonds (editor) (1991). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=syOABwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=RA2-PA105"><i>The Black women oral history project: from the Arthur and Elizabeth Schlesinger Library on the History of Women in America, Radcliffe College</i></a> (reprint ed.). Berlin, Germany: Walter de Gruyter. p.&#160;105. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-3-110-97391-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-3-110-97391-4">978-3-110-97391-4</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">August 9,</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASue+Bailey+Thurman&amp;rft.aufirst=Ruth+Edmonds+%28editor%29&amp;rft.aulast=Hill&amp;rft.btitle=The+Black+women+oral+history+project%3A+from+the+Arthur+and+Elizabeth+Schlesinger+Library+on+the+History+of+Women+in+America%2C+Radcliffe+College&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.edition=reprint&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-3-110-97391-4&amp;rft.pages=105&amp;rft.place=Berlin%2C+Germany&amp;rft.pub=Walter+de+Gruyter&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com.mx%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DsyOABwAAQBAJ%26pg%3DRA2-PA105&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span><span class="citation-comment" style="display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em">CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_a